Both `transcript.json` and `analysis_summary.txt` are in the working directory.

Headline finding: the dominant treatment-effect heterogeneity signal is for **venetoclax+azacitidine**, with the joint subgroup `npm1_mutation=1 AND unfit_for_intensive=1 AND tp53_mutation=0 AND complex_karyotype=0` (n=4,531). Within this subgroup ORR is 78.6% on VEN+AZA vs 15.8% off (Δ=+62.8 pp; adjusted interaction OR≈21, p=3.3e-296); outside it the effect is null (16.4% vs 16.7%). The 4-predicate definition includes both required positive markers (NPM1+, unfit) and the two suppressor variables (TP53-, complex_karyotype-) whose unfavorable values abolish the benefit.

Other findings: classical targeted-therapy × biomarker pairings (midostaurin/gilteritinib × FLT3, ivosidenib × IDH1, enasidenib × IDH2) were not recapitulated; only a small enasidenib × sex_female interaction (Δ≈+2.5 pp in females, −2.3 pp in males; p=2e-4) and a small 7+3 × complex_karyotype interaction were detected. ECOG, complex_karyotype, TP53, blast %, and WBC reduce ORR; NPM1 and albumin raise it.
